article.description:
Amanda Lassiter is known as a shooter only to her
Seattle Storm teammates.
article.headline: Storm beat Liberty for first time ever
article.linkText: Lassiter's hot hand helps Storm defeat Liberty
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Amanda Lassiter is known as a shooter only to her Seattle Storm teammates. Lassiter displayed her skills Wednesday when she made all four of her 3-point attempts and scored a career-high 16 points -- all in the first half -- in a 75-65 victory over the New York Liberty. Lassiter, who averages 3.7 points, exploited the Liberty's plan of packing the defense inside to stop WNBA leader scorer Lauren Jackson. With defenders draped over Jackson, Lassiter -- 7-for-28 on 3s this season -- took advantage and made several open looks. "I wasn't surprised," Storm guard Sue Bird said. "She definitely has that ability. You see it in practice, she just hasn't showed it in games." The Liberty, however, were caught completely offguard by Lassiter's shooting touch. "Our defensive scheme was to make her beat us," guard Vickie Johnson said. "We really didn't have confidence in her shot." "Lassiter was shooting 25 percent on 3s," Liberty coach Richie Adubato said. "We can't even get our great shooters to go 4-for-4 on 3s." Seattle (12-9) recorded its first victory ever over the Liberty (9-9) and avoided its first three-game losing streak since starting the season 0-3. The Liberty had a two-game winning streak snapped and dropped to 1-6 on the road. Lassiter's outburst helped the Storm build a 22-point lead in the first half, despite getting only seven points from Bird and Jackson. She also forced New York to play perimeter defense, which freed up Jackson inside. "When they double and triple team me, I have to give my teammates a chance," Jackson said. "When they shoot well, like Amanda did, it makes it easier for me." Jackson scored 22 of her 27 points in the second half, including 14 in the final seven minutes after New York cut the lead to 59-49. "They're a good team, we knew they were going to make a run," Storm coach Ann Donovan said. "We kept our focus and got our shots. It was a good win to get us rolling again." Bird, who has been out with a sore knee, played 36 minutes. She scored seven points and handed out eight assists. "She is trying to play through it," Donovan said. "But you can tell she's not 100 percent, that's pretty clear." Johnson scored 13 of her 17 points in the second half for the Liberty. Tari Phillips and Tamika Whitmore added 10 points apiece. Kamila Vodichkova added 14 points for Seattle.

Game notes
Seattle had lost four previous games against New York. ... Seattle activated forward Alisa Burras on Tuesday and placed center/forward Danielle McCulley on the injured list with right shoulder tendinitis. Burras missed five games on the injured list with a right knee injury. ... Seattle improved to 6-2 against the Eastern Conference.
